The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Durban (PTI): Mahatma Gandhis great-grand-daughter is among the prospective buyers vying to purchase the house where he lived in Johannesburg for a year.           cy Ball, the owner of the house, said: The great-granddaughter of Gandhi, Kirti Menon, and a Malaysian businessman want to convert the house into a Gandhi Centre.                  
	 Mumbai/New Delhi (PTI): The CBI on Monday said it might question Sarobjit Singhs father-in-law in the alleged Rs 1 crore bribery case. The agencys investigations revealed that Sarobjit used his father-in-laws cellphone to make calls to alleged hawala operators. In Delhi, Sarobjits father and former Union minister Buta Singh iterated he would cooperate with the CBI.                  
	 Kanpur (PTI): The atomic energy department has rejected citing security reasons IIT Kanpurs proposal of setting up a small nuclear reactor on its campus. The IIT, which will try to convince the department at the International Nuclear Meet in November, said it had sought to set up the reactor for MTech students pursuing nuclear engineering.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Centre on Monday said it would set up 71 additional special courts for speedy trial of cases. The government has decided to set up 71 additional special courts for trial of cases investigated by the CBI, law minister M. Veerappa Moily told the Rajya Sabha.                  
	Shravasti (PTI): Three poachers allegedly killed two peacocks in the reserve area of Bhinga forest in Uttar Pradeshs Shravasti district. One of the poachers have been arrested. Search is on for the other two.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Over 400 educational institutions have been granted minority status this year so far, the government informed the Lok Sabha on Monday. While 1,396 institutions were given the minority tag last year, the figure was 950 in 2007 and 1,684 in 2006.                                                                                                                           
